Consecutive.

The development of consecutive constructions is very similar to that of final ς osten only distinct by the context. Examples: Men. 572

habent hunc morem argentarii: cluentes sibi uolunt multos. Il. 111. 286 τιμὴν δ’ Ἀργείοις ἀποτινέμεν...ἥ τε πέληται.

The subjunctive is used in consecutive sentences ‘as being the only mood which can shew that the action of the main sentence is limited by the circumstances which accompany or follow the subordinate sentence.’ Schmalz.
